
The PackBuffer and UnPackBuffer classes provide a convenient mechanism
for packing and unpacking buffers for communication.  They are
currently implemented for use with MPI, with which they use MPI's Pack
and UnPack routines.


The PackBuffer class dynamically resizes its internal buffer to contain
enough memory to pack the entire object.  When deleted, this internal buffer
is deleted.

const char* buf()

  This method returns a pointer to the internal buffer.

int len()

  This method returns the amount of memory used to pack the data.

void reset()

  This method resets the pointer used for packing, which effectively resets
  the PackBuffer class to pack new data.
 
void pack(const <type>* data, const int num=1)
void pack(const <type>& data)

  The pack methods are defined for a variety of standard data types.
  The first pack method can be used to pack a vector of <type>'s, and the
  second pack method can be used to pack a single <type>.

PackBuffer& operator<< (PackBuffer& buff, const <type>& data) 

  The in-stream operator provides a convenient shorthand for the second
  pack method.



The UnPackBuffer class retrieves information from a given buffer.

void setup(char* buf_, int size_)

  This method sets the buffer and buffer size and resets the buffer to prepare
  it for retrieval.
 
UnPackBuffer(char* buf_=0, int size_=0)

  The construct simply calls the setup method.

~UnPackBuffer()

  The destructor deletes the buffer supplied to the setup or to the constructor.
 
const char* buf()

  This method returns a pointer to the buffer.

int len()

  This method returns the current index used to retrieve information from the 
  buffer;

void reset()

  This method resets the buffer, which enables this class to retrieve information
  from the same buffer again.

void unpack(const <type>* data, const int num=1)
void unpack(const <type>& data)

  The unpack methods are defined for a variety of standard data types.
  The first unpack method can be used to unpack a vector of <type>'s, and the
  second unpack method can be used to unpack a single <type>.
 

UnPackBuffer& operator>> (UnPackBuffer& buff, const <type>& data)

  The out-stream operator provides a convenient shorthand for the second
  unpack method.
